---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import LessonCard from "../components/ui/LessonCard.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Mathematics & Computer Science Through Stories"
  description="Mathematics and computer science taught through real problems that changed history."
>

<!-- ============================================================== HERO -->

<section class="relative pt-20 pb-10 overflow-hidden bg-navy px-8 md:px-20">
  <!-- Perspective grid — vanishing point top-right -->
  <div class="absolute inset-0 overflow-hidden opacity-[0.06]">
    <svg viewBox="0 0 1200 800" preserveAspectRatio="xMidYMid slice" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="w-full h-full">
      <line x1="0" y1="800" x2="1200" y2="200" stroke="#c8a44a" stroke-width="0.5"/>
      <line x1="0" y1="680" x2="1200" y2="230" stroke="#c8a44a" stroke-width="0.5"/>
      <line x1="0" y1="560" x2="1200" y2="260" stroke="#c8a44a" stroke-width="0.5"/>
      <line x1="0" y1="440" x2="1200" y2="290" stroke="#c8a44a" stroke-width="0.5"/>
      <line x1="0" y1="320" x2="1200" y2="310" stroke="#c8a44a" stroke-width="0.5"/>
      <line x1="0" y1="200" x2="1200" y2="320" stroke="#c8a44a" stroke-width="0.5"/>
      <line x1="0"    y1="800" x2="1200" y2="0" stroke="#c8a44a" stroke-width="0.5"/>
      <line x1="200"  y1="800" x2="1200" y2="0" stroke="#c8a44a" stroke-width="0.5"/>
      <line x1="400"  y1="800" x2="1200" y2="0" stroke="#c8a44a" stroke-width="0.5"/>
      <line x1="600"  y1="800" x2="1200" y2="0" stroke="#c8a44a" stroke-width="0.5"/>
      <line x1="800"  y1="800" x2="1200" y2="0" stroke="#c8a44a" stroke-width="0.5"/>
      <line x1="1000" y1="800" x2="1200" y2="0" stroke="#c8a44a" stroke-width="0.5"/>
    </svg>
  </div>

  <div class="max-w-3xl relative">
    <p class="font-mono text-xs text-amber/70 tracking-widest mb-6 uppercase">A different way to learn mathematics &amp; computer science</p>

    <h1 class="font-serif text-5xl md:text-6xl lg:text-7xl text-ivory leading-tight mb-8">
      Mathematics &amp; CS<br />
      <span class="text-amber">through stories.</span>
    </h1>

    <p class="text-xl md:text-2xl text-ivory-dim leading-relaxed mb-10 max-w-2xl">
      Every great mathematical idea emerged to solve a real problem that
      mattered. Here, we teach it that way &mdash; starting with the problem,
      letting the concept appear as the natural solution, then following it
      forward into the present.
    </p>

    <a href="#lessons"
       class="inline-flex items-center gap-3 border border-amber/40 rounded-full px-6 py-3 font-sans text-sm text-amber hover:bg-amber/10 transition-all">
      <span>Explore the lessons</span>
      <svg class="w-4 h-4" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2">
        <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" />
      </svg>
    </a>
  </div>
</section>


<!-- ============================================================ MANIFESTO -->

<section class="bg-navy-medium py-24 px-8 md:px-20">
  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
    <p class="font-mono text-xs text-amber/70 tracking-widest mb-8 uppercase">The idea behind this</p>

    <h2 class="font-serif text-3xl md:text-4xl text-ivory mb-10 leading-tight">
      The textbook gets it backwards.
    </h2>

    <div class="space-y-6 text-lg text-ivory/90 leading-relaxed">
      <p>
        The standard approach: here is a definition, here is a theorem, here is
        a contrived example. Learn the abstraction first; applications come later,
        if at all. For most students, &ldquo;later&rdquo; never arrives. The
        theorem remains inert &mdash; a thing to pass an exam, not a tool with a history.
      </p>

      <p>
        But every great theorem was born as an answer to something urgent.
        Bayes&rsquo; theorem became powerful because Turing needed to eliminate
        10&sup2;&sup3; cipher settings before midnight. Shannon&rsquo;s entropy
        emerged because the U.S. government needed to send a president&rsquo;s voice
        across the Atlantic without letting the enemy hear it. The concept and the
        context are inseparable.
      </p>

      <p>
        Each lesson here starts with a real problem &mdash; one that actually had
        stakes, where getting the mathematics wrong had consequences. The concept
        emerges as the <em>only</em> natural solution to that problem. Then we
        follow it forward to show where it lives in the world right now.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-12 grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-6">
      {[
        {
          step: "01",
          title: "The Problem",
          desc: "A real historical situation. The pressure is genuine. The need for a solution is not academic."
        },
        {
          step: "02",
          title: "The Mathematics",
          desc: "The concept emerges from the problem — proved rigorously, but motivated first."
        },
        {
          step: "03",
          title: "The Code",
          desc: "Python notebooks build the solution from scratch. Run it yourself. Break things."
        },
      ].map(({ step, title, desc }) => (
        <div class="border border-ivory-dim/15 rounded-lg p-6 bg-navy-light/40">
          <p class="font-mono text-sm text-amber/80 mb-3 font-semibold">{step}</p>
          <p class="font-sans font-semibold text-ivory text-base mb-2">{title}</p>
          <p class="text-base text-ivory/80 leading-relaxed">{desc}</p>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>
  </div>
</section>


<!-- ============================================================== LESSONS -->

<section id="lessons" class="py-16 px-8 md:px-20 bg-navy">
  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
    <p class="font-mono text-xs text-amber/70 tracking-widest mb-3 uppercase">The lessons</p>
    <h2 class="font-serif text-3xl text-ivory mb-8">Choose where to start.</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <LessonCard
        number={1}
        title="Bayes' Theorem"
        tagline="How a 178-year-old formula broke the Enigma cipher"
        subjects="Probability Theory · Python"
        href="/lessons/enigma-bayes"
        narrativeHook="Bletchley Park, 1941. The German Navy is sinking Allied convoys faster than they can be replaced. Alan Turing has 10²³ possible cipher settings and eighteen hours."
      />

      <LessonCard
        number={2}
        title="Information Theory"
        tagline="How Claude Shannon invented the mathematics of communication"
        subjects="Information Theory · Python"
        href="/lessons/information-theory"
        narrativeHook="Bell Labs, 1943. The U.S. government needs to send a president's voice across the Atlantic without the Nazis intercepting it. Claude Shannon has to figure out what 'information' actually is."
      />
    </div>
  </div>
</section>


<!-- ============================================================== FOOTER -->

<footer class="bg-navy-medium border-t border-ivory-dim/10 py-10 px-8 text-center font-sans">
  <p class="text-ivory-dim/50 text-sm mb-1">
    Built with <a href="https://astro.build" class="text-amber/70 hover:text-amber transition-colors">Astro</a>.
    Deployed on <a href="https://netlify.com" class="text-amber/70 hover:text-amber transition-colors">Netlify</a>.
    Notebooks run Python&nbsp;3.12.
  </p>
</footer>

</BaseLayout>
